{"title_page": "1984 Freedom Bowl", "text_new": "{{Infobox NCAA football yearly game\n| Game Name          = Freedom Bowl\n| Optional Subheader = Inaugural Freedom Bowl Game\n| Title Sponsor      =\n| Image              =\n| Caption            =\n| Date Game Played   = December 26\n| Year Game Played   = 1984\n| Football Season    = 1984\n| Stadium            = [[Angel Stadium of Anaheim|Anaheim Stadium]]\n| City               = [[Anaheim, California|Anaheim, CA]]\n| Visitor Name Short = Texas\n| Visitor Nickname   = Longhorns\n| Visitor Record     = 7\u20133\u20131\n| Visitor AP         = 19\n| Visitor Coaches    = 20\n| Visitor Coach      = [[Fred Akers]]\n| Visitor1           = 0\n| Visitor2           = 17\n| Visitor3           = 0\n| Visitor4           = 0\n| Home Name Short    = Iowa\n| Home Nickname      = Hawkeyes\n| Home Record        = 7\u20134\u20131\n| Home AP            =\n| Home Coaches       =\n| Home Coach         = [[Hayden Fry]]\n| Home1              = 14\n| Home2              = 10\n| Home3              = 31\n| Home4              = 0\n| MVP                = [[Chuck Long]] (Iowa QB)<ref name=\"BowlMVP\">{{cite web |url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/2012/Bowls.pdf |title=Bowl/All-Star Game Records: Most Valuable Players in Former Major Bowls |author=National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) |work=2012 NCAA Division I Football Records |page=94 |publisher=NCAA.org |accessdate=January 3, 2015 |format=PDF}}</ref><br>William Harris (Texas TE)<ref name=\"BowlMVP\" />\n| Odds               =\n| Anthem             =\n| Referee         = Jack Gatto<br>[[Mike Pereira]] (Line Judge)\n| Halftime           =\n| Attendance         = 24,093\n| Payout             =\n| US Network         = TCS/Metrosports\n| US Announcers      = [[Sam Nover]] and [[Jack Snow (American football)|Jack Snow]] \n| Ratings            =\n| Different Next     = [[1985 Freedom Bowl|1985]]\n| FirstGameEverPlayed=yes\n}}\nThe '''1984 Freedom Bowl''' was an American [[college football]] [[bowl game]] played on December 26, 1984, at [[Angel Stadium of Anaheim|Anaheim Stadium]] in [[Anaheim, California|Anaheim, CA]]. The inaugural edition of the [[Freedom Bowl]] matched the #19 [[1984 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas Longhorns]] of the [[Southwest Conference]] and the [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]]'s [[1984 Iowa Hawkeyes football team|Iowa Hawkeyes]]. After leading 24\u201317 at halftime, the Hawkeyes blew the game open with 31 unanswered points in the third quarter to win 55\u201317.\n\n==Background==\nThe Longhorns started the season ranked #4 in the polls, and they beat #11 Auburn and #4 Penn State to rise to #1 in the polls. After a win over Rice, they tied #3 Oklahoma to fall to #3. Wins over Arkansas, #14 SMU, and Texas Tech soon followed. However, they lost to Houston at home, making them fall to #10. A win over #12 TCU was their last of the season, as they fell to Baylor and Texas A&M to close out the year, while finishing tied for second in the [[Southwest Conference]] with TCU and Arkansas, while SMU and Houston shared the crown. This was their 8th straight bowl appearance. Iowa began the year ranked #10 in the polls, and they won their opening game versus rival Iowa State to rise to #5. Losses to #12 Penn State and #5 Ohio State made them fall out of the polls. Five straight wins (including a win over #14 Purdue) made them rise back up to #17. They tied with Wisconsin 10-10, but a loss to Michigan State the following week made them fall out of the polls permanently. A loss to Minnesota was followed by a win over Hawaii to close out the regular season. They finished in third place in the [[Big Ten Conference]], behind Ohio State, and tied 2nd placers Illinois & Purdue. This was Iowa's fourth straight bowl appearance.\n\n==Game summary==\nIowa\u2019s Chuck Long threw for 461 yards and a bowl-record<ref name=\"MVP\">{{cite web |url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/2012/Bowls.pdf |title=Bowl/All-Star Game Records: Individual Record Lists |author=National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) |work=2012 NCAA Division I Football Records |page=42 |publisher=NCAA.org |accessdate=January 3, 2015 |format=PDF}}</ref> six touchdowns.<ref name=\"Game1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/12/27/sports/long-sets-records-as-iowa-triumphs.html|title=Long Sets Records As Iowa Triumphs|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 27, 1984|accessdate=January 3, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Game2\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-12-29/sports/sp-2869_1_freedom-bowl|title=FREEDOM BOWL : Charting Freedom's Trail : 1984|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 29, 1992|accessdate=January 3, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Game3\">{{cite news|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1984/12/27/page/41/article/long-nearly-perfect-iowa-rips-texas |title=Long nearly perfect, Iowa rips Texas |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=December 27, 1984|accessdate=November 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Team statistics===\n<!--\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!  !! Texas !! Iowa\n|-\n| First Downs || 15 || 28\n|-\n| Rushing Yards || 35-115 || 41-91\n|-\n| Passing || 17-34-2 || 30-40-0\n|-\n| Passing Yards || 185 || 469\n|-\n| Total Offense || 300 || 560\n|-\n| Fumbles Lost || 3-3 || 5-2\n|-\n| Punts-Average || 5-43.0 || 4-42.0\n|-\n| Penalties || 6-50 || 4-27\n|-\n|}-->\n\n{{AmFootballGameStatistics\n| Visitor        = Texas Longhorns\n| VisitorDisplay = Texas\n| Home           = Iowa Hawkeyes\n| HomeDisplay    = Iowa\n| VisFirsts      = 15\n| VisPlaysYds    = 69-300\n| VisRushing     = 15-115\n| VisPassYds     = 185\n| VisPassing     = 17-34-2\n| VisTOP         = \n| HomeFirsts     = 28\n| HomePlaysYds   = 81-560\n| HomeRushing    = 41-91\n| HomePassYds    = 469\n| HomePassing    = 30-40-0\n| HomeTOP        = \n}}\n\n===Individual leaders===\n<!--\n'''Passing'''<br>\nTexas: Dodge &ndash; 16-32, 180 yds, 2 TD, 2 INT<br>\nIowa: Long &ndash; 29-39, 461 yds, 6 TD\n\n'''Rushing'''<br>\nTexas: Orr