es football team|Iowa Hawkeyes]]. After leading 24\u201317 at halftime, the Hawkeyes blew the game open with 31 unanswered points in the third quarter to win 55\u201317.\n\n==Background==\nThe Longhorns started the season ranked #4 in the polls, and they beat #11 Auburn and #4 Penn State to rise to #1 in the polls. After a win over Rice, they tied #3 Oklahoma to fall to #3. Wins over Arkansas, #14 SMU, and Texas Tech soon followed. However, they lost to Houston at home, making them fall to #10. A win over #12 TCU was their last of the season, as they fell to Baylor and Texas A&M to close out the year, while finishing tied for second in the [[Southwest Conference]] with TCU and Arkansas, while SMU and Houston shared the crown. This was their 8th straight bowl appearance. Iowa began the year ranked #10 in the polls, and they won their opening game versus rival Iowa State to rise to #5. Losses to #12 Penn State and #5 Ohio State made them fall out of the polls. Five straight wins (including a win over #14 Purdue) made them rise back up to #17. They tied with Wisconsin 10-10, but a loss to Michigan State the following week made them fall out of the polls permanently. A loss to Minnesota was followed by a win over Hawaii to close out the regular season. They finished in third place in the [[Big Ten Conference]], behind Ohio State, and tied 2nd placers Illinois & Purdue. This was Iowa's fourth straight bowl appearance.\n\n==Game summary==\nIowa\u2019s Chuck Long threw for 461 yards and a bowl-record<ref name=\"MVP\">{{cite web |url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/2012/Bowls.pdf |title=Bowl/All-Star Game Records: Individual Record Lists |author=National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) |work=2012 NCAA Division I Football Records |page=42 |publisher=NCAA.org |accessdate=January 3, 2015 |format=PDF}}</ref> six touchdowns.<ref name=\"Game1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/12/27/sports/long-sets-records-as-iowa-triumphs.html|title=Long Sets Records As Iowa Triumphs|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=December 27, 1984|accessdate=January 3, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Game2\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-12-29/sports/sp-2869_1_freedom-bowl|title=FREEDOM BOWL : Charting Freedom's Trail : 1984|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 29, 1992|accessdate=January 3, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Game3\">{{cite news|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1984/12/27/page/41/article/long-nearly-perfect-iowa-rips-texas |title=Long nearly perfect, Iowa rips Texas |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=December 27, 1984|accessdate=November 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Team statistics===\n<!--\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!  !! Texas !! Iowa\n|-\n| First Downs || 15 || 28\n|-\n| Rushing Yards || 35-115 || 41-91\n|-\n| Passing || 17-34-2 || 30-40-0\n|-\n| Passing Yards || 185 || 469\n|-\n| Total Offense || 300 || 560\n|-\n| Fumbles Lost || 3-3 || 5-2\n|-\n| Punts-Average || 5-43.0 || 4-42.0\n|-\n| Penalties || 6-50 || 4-27\n|-\n|}-->\n\n{{AmFootballGameStatistics\n| Visitor        = Texas Longhorns\n| VisitorDisplay = Texas\n| Home           = Iowa Hawkeyes\n| HomeDisplay    = Iowa\n| VisFirsts      = 15\n| VisPlaysYds    = 69-300\n| VisRushing     = 15-115\n| VisPassYds     = 185\n| VisPassing     = 17-34-2\n| VisTOP         = \n| HomeFirsts     = 28\n| HomePlaysYds   = 81-560\n| HomeRushing    = 41-91\n| HomePassYds    = 469\n| HomePassing    = 30-40-0\n| HomeTOP        = \n}}\n\n===Individual leaders===\n<!--\n'''Passing'''<br>\nTexas: Dodge &ndash; 16-32, 180 yds, 2 TD, 2 INT<br>\nIowa: Long &ndash; 29-39, 461 yds, 6 TD\n\n'''Rushing'''<br>\nTexas: Orr &ndash; 12 carries, 67 yds; Johnson &ndash; 8 carries, 56 yds<br>\nIowa: Gill &ndash; 17 carries, 61 yds\n\n'''Receiving'''<br>\nTexas: Bryant &ndash; 3 catches, 50 yds, 1 TD; Duhon &ndash; 1 catch, 47 yds<br>\nIowa: Smith &ndash; 4 catches, 115 yds, 1 TD; Happel &ndash; 8 catches, 104 yds, 1 TD\n-->\n\n{{AmFootballGameTopPlayers\n| Visitor            = Texas Longhorns\n| VisitorDisplay     = Texas\n| Home               = Iowa Hawkeyes\n| HomeDisplay        = Iowa\n| VisPasser          = Dodge\n| VisPassStats       = 16-32, 180 yds, 2 TD, 2 INT\n| VisRusher          = Orr<br>Johnson\n| VisRushStats       = 12 carries, 67 yds;<br>8 carries, 56 yds\n| VisReceiver        = Bryant<br>Duhon\n| VisReceivingStats  = 3 catches, 50 yds, 1 TD;<br>1 catch, 47 yds\n| HomePasser         = [[Chuck Long]]\n| HomePassStats      = 29-39, 461 yds, 6 TD\n| HomeRusher         = [[Owen Gill]]\n| HomeRushStats      = 17 carries, 61 yds\n| HomeReceiver       = Robert Smith<br>Bill Happel\n| HomeReceivingStats = 4 catches, 115 yds, 1 TD;<br>8 catches, 104 yds, 1 TD\n}}\n\n<ref>[http://www.mattybproductions.com/iowafootball/bowlgames/1984freedom.html Box score]</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Longhorns made just two more bowl games in the decade, while Iowa made four more in the decade.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{1984 bowl game navbox}}\n{{Freedom Bowl navbox}}\n{{Iowa Hawkeyes bowl game navbox}}\n{{Texas Longhorns bowl game navbox}}\n\n[[Category:1984\u201385 NCAA football bowl games|Freedom Bow]]\n[[Category:Freedom Bowl]]\n[[Category:Iowa Hawkeyes football bowl games]]\n[[Category:Texas Longhorns football bowl games]]\n[[Category:1984 in sports in California|Free]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGame summary:the work's name is \"The New York Times\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1984_Freedom_Bowl"}
{"title_page": "1984 (1956 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1956 film by Michael Anderson}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = 1984\n| image          = 1984film.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Michael Anderson (director)|Michael Anderson]]\n| producer       = N. Peter Rathvon\n| screenplay    = {{Plainlist|\n* Ralph Gilbert Bettison\n* [[William Templeton (screenwriter)|William Templeton]]\n}}\n| based on   = {{based on|''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four]]''|[[George Orwell]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Edmond O'Brien]]\n* [[Michael Redgrave]]\n* [[Jan Sterling]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Malcolm Arnold]]\n| cinematography = [[C.M. Pennington-Richards]]\n| editing        = Bill Lewthwaite\n| studio         = Holiday Film Productions Ltd.\n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1956|03|06|UK|1956|09||US|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/1984-1970-1 | title=''1984'' | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref>\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]80,073<ref>{{cite journal |first=Vincent |last=Porter |title=The Robert Clark Account: Films released in Britain by Associated British Pictures, British Lion, MGM, and Warner Bros., 1946\u20131957 |journal=[[Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television]] |volume=20 |issue=4 |year=2000 |pages=469\u2013511 [p. 510] |doi=10.1080/713669742 }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''1984''''' is a 1956 British [[black-and-white]] [[science fiction film]], based on the novel ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four]]'' by [[George Orwell]], depicting a [[totalitarian]] future society. \n\nThis is the first film adaptation of the story, directed by [[Michael Anderson (director)|Michael Anderson]] and starring [[Edmond O'Brien]] as protagonist [[Winston Smith]], and featuring [[Donald Pleasence]], [[Jan Sterling]], and [[Michael Redgrave]]. The character [[O'Brien (1984)|O'Brien]], the antagonist, was renamed \"O'Connor\", due to the shared surname of the actor Edmond O'Brien. [[Emmanuel Goldstein]] is changed to \"Kalador\".\n\nFor the U.S. market, ''1984'' was distributed in 1956 on a [[double feature]] with another British science fiction film, ''[[The Gamma People]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McGee|first1=Mark Thomas|last2=Robertson|first2=R.J.|date=2013|title=You Won't Believe Your Eyes|publisher=Bear Manor Media|location=Orlando, Florida|ISBN=978-1-59393-273-2|page=254}}</ref> After distributor agreements expired, the film was withdrawn from theatrical and TV distribution channels by Orwell's estate and has not been obtainable legally for many years.\n\nIn 1954, [[Peter Cushing]] and [[Andre Morell]] starred in a [[BBC|BBC-TV]] [[Nineteen Eighty-Four (UK TV programme)|made-for-TV adaptation]] which was extremely popular with British audiences, leading to the production of the 1956 O'Brien theatrical film version. Pleasence had also appeared in the BBC television version, playing the character of Syme, which for the film was amalgamated with that of the character Parsons.\n\nLike the [[Animal Farm (1954 film)|earlier film adaption]] of ''[[Animal Farm]]'', ''1984'' was secretly funded by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Morris|first1=Nigel|title=Keeping It All in the (Nuclear) Family: Big Brother, Auntie BBC, Uncle Sam and George Orwell\u2019s Nineteen Eighty-Four|journal=Frames Cinema Journal|url=http://framescinemajournal.com/article/keeping-it-all-in-the-nuclear-family-big-brother-auntie-bbc-uncle-sam-and-george-orwells-nineteen-eighty-four/}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA voice-over narrator explains that in the mid-1950s, a [[nuclear war]] and devastation of Earth gave rise to [[Nations of Nineteen Eighty-Four|three superstates]]: Oceania, Eurasia, and East Asia. By 1984, London, with its bomb-proof ministry, is designated as the capital of Airstrip One, a province of Oceania, controlled by one all-powerful Party, embodied by the figurehead [[Big Brother (1984)|Big Brother]].\n\nIn the spring of 1984, [[Winston Smith]], a member of the elite Outer Party, encounters [[Julia (1984)|Julia]], a woman he suspects may be a member of the [[Thought Police]]. Winston returns to his apartment, where an electronic surveillance eye examines the contents of his briefcase. Smuggling a small black diary past the eye, Winston begins to write down the subversive thoughts he fears to say aloud. Winston's reverie is interrupted when Selina Parsons, a little girl who lives next door, enters his apartment to practice denouncing him as a traitor. Robert Parsons, Selina's father, invites Winston to join him at the local Chestnut Tree caf\u00e9.\n\nAt the cafe, Winston and Parsons spot Rutherford and Jones, two Outer Party traitors who have been rehabilitated by the government's Ministry of Love. Afterwards, Winston goes to a junk shop to wonder at the objects of yesteryear that are now deemed worthless. Julia enters the shop, sending Winston scurrying into the street, where he is stopped by the police and ordered to report to Administration the next morning.\n\nAt the Administration the next day, a party officer reprimands Winston for socializing with the common masses. Winston then proceeds to his job at the Records Department at the Ministry of Truth. When Winston discovers a photo that would prove Jones and Rutherford innocent, [[O'Brien (1984)|O'Connor]], Winston's superior, instructs him to destroy it.\n\nThat evening, at a political rally, Julia passes Winston a note professing her love to him. Later, they arrange to meet Sunday in a meadow outside London, far from the prying microphones and monitors of Big Brother. There, they touch each other, an act prohibited by the Anti-Sex League, and proceed to make love.\n\nTwo weeks later, Winston proposes renting a room at the junk store, one of the few places free of the omnipresent monitors. In the sanctity of their quarters, Winston confides that he believes O'Connor may be a member of the Underground.\n\nOne night, Winston finds a note written in O'Connor's handwriting that reads \"down with Big Brother.\" Convinced that O'Connor represents their only hope to break free of the tyranny of Big Brother, Julia and Winston go to his apartment and declare that they want to join the Underground. O'Connor instructs Winston to carry an empty briefcase with him at all times.\n\nA few days later, during a rally to launch Hate Week, a man switches briefcases with Winston. When Winston opens the case, he finds a copy of a treatise by the alleged leader of the Underground. Back in their secret room, Julia muses that only love can defeat Big Brother. At that moment, a telescreen hidden behind a mirror condemns Julia's sentiments, after which, the police burst in to arrest them.\n\nAt the Ministry of Love, Winston is confined in a pit-like room. Soon after, Parsons is thrown into the pit, his daughter having denounced him for muttering in his sleep \"Down with Big Brother.\" After Parsons is taken away, O'Connor enters the room and reveals himself to be a covert agent of the state. Under O'Connor's direction, Winston is subjected to a brainwashing campaign. Still resistant after a series of electroshock treatments, Winston declares that the party will never eradicate his love for Julia. Having ascertained that Winston's worst fear is being eaten alive by rats, O'Connor confines him in a room filled with the squealing rodents, after which Winston breaks down and begs them to feed Julia to the rodents instead.\n\nAfter O'Connor authorizes his release, Winston mindlessly wanders through the streets, where he spots Julia. After they confess their mutual betrayal, Big Brother broadcasts that the Eurasian army has been routed in battle and that the war will be soon over. In the final shot, the rehabilitated and brainwashed Winston and Julia then fervently join the crowd in cheering \"Long live Big Brother!\"\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Edmond O'Brien]] as [[Winston Smith]]\n* [[Michael Redgrave]] as [[O'Brien (Nineteen Eighty-Four)|General O'Connor]]\n* [[Jan Sterling]] as [[Julia (Nineteen Eighty-Four)|Julia]]\n* [[David Kossoff]] as Charrington\n* [[Mervyn Johns]] as Jones\n* [[Donald Pleasence]] as R. Parsons\n* Carol Wolveridge as Selina Parsons\n* [[Ernest Clark]] as Outer Party Announcer\n* [[Patrick Allen]] as Inner Party Official\n* [[Michael Ripper]] as Outer Party Orator\n* [[Ewen Solon]] as Outer Party Orator\n* [[Kenneth Griffith]] as Prisoner\n\n==Reception==\n''[[The New York Times]]'' reviewer [[A.H. Weiler]]  called this film adaptation a stark, sober and thoughtful, if not altogether persuasive, film.\" He said the film  The \"director and the scenarists have adapted the book 'freely.' But they have retained its essential spirit and ideas in the film.\"<ref name=\"Weller\">{{cite news |last1=Weiler |first1=A. H. |title=The Screen: '1984' Opens; Adaptation of Orwell's Novel at Normandie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/10/01/archives/the-screen-1984-opens-adaptation-of-orwells-novel-at-normandie.html |accessdate=30 November 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=1 October 1956}}</ref> A ''[[The Boston Globe|Boston Globe]]'' reviewer said that \"the film had the same sense of bleak horror and black apprehension that Orwell developed when freedom was allowed to die.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39863267/screen_arrivals_pilgrim_offers_grim/|title=SCREEN ARRIVALS: Pilgrim Offers Grim '1984'|last=Adams|first=Marjorie|date=1956-07-26|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=2019-11-30|pages=19}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of films featuring surveillance]]\n*[[List of films that depict class struggle]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0048918|title=1984}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|1209731-1984|1984}}\n\n{{Nineteen Eighty-Four}}\n{{Michael Anderson}}\n<!--Split film/book article intentional - Please do not remove this comment-->\n\n[[Category:1956 films]]\n[[Category:1950s science fiction drama films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British science fiction drama films]]\n[[Category:British black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films based on Nineteen Eighty-Four]]\n[[Category:Dystopian films]]\n[[Category:Films about freedom of expression]]\n[[Category:Mass surveillance in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films set in the future]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1984]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Michael Anderson]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Malcolm Arnold]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1956 film by Michael Anderson}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = 1984\n| image          = 1984film.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Michael Anderson (director)|Michael Anderson]]\n| producer       = N. Peter Rathvon\n| screenplay    = {{Plainlist|\n* Ralph Gilbert Bettison\n* [[William Templeton (screenwriter)|William Templeton]]\n}}\n| based on   = {{based on|''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four]]''|[[George Orwell]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Edmond O'Brien]]\n* [[Michael Redgrave]]\n* [[Jan Sterling]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Malcolm Arnold]]\n| cinematography = [[C.M. Pennington-Richards]]\n| editing        = Bill Lewthwaite\n| studio         = Holiday Film Productions Ltd.\n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1956|03|06|UK|1956|09||US|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/1984-1970-1 | title=''1984'' | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref>\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]80,073<ref>{{cite journal |first=Vincent |last=Porter |title=The Robert Clark Account: Films released in Britain by Associated British Pictures, British Lion, MGM, and Warner Bros., 1946\u20131957 |journal=[[Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television]] |volume=20 |issue=4 |year=2000 |pages=469\u2013511 [p. 510] |doi=10.1080/713669742 }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''1984''''' is a 1956 British [[black-and-white]] [[science fiction film]], based on the novel ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four]]'' by [[George Orwell]], depicting a [[totalitarian]] future society. \n\nThis is the first film adaptation of the story, directed by [[Michael Anderson (director)|Michael Anderson]] and starring [[Edmond O'Brien]] as protagonist [[Winston Smith]], and featuring [[Donald Pleasence]], [[Jan Sterling]], and [[Michael Redgrave]]. The character [[O'Brien (1984)|O'Brien]], the antagonist, was renamed \"O'Connor\", due to the shared surname of the actor Edmond O'Brien. [[Emmanuel Goldstein]] is changed to \"Kalador\".\n\nFor the U.S. market, ''1984'' was distributed in 1956 on a [[double feature]] with another British science fiction film, ''[[The Gamma People]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McGee|first1=Mark Thomas|last2=Robertson|first2=R.J.|date=2013|title=You Won't Believe Your Eyes|publisher=Bear Manor Media|location=Orlando, Florida|ISBN=978-1-59393-273-2|page=254}}</ref> After distributor agreements expired, the film was withdrawn from theatrical and TV distribution channels by Orwell's estate and has not been obtainable legally for many years.\n\nIn 1954, [[Peter Cushing]] and [[Andre Morell]] starred in a [[BBC|BBC-TV]] [[Nineteen Eighty-Four (UK TV programme)|made-for-TV adaptation]] which was extremely popular with British audiences, leading to the production of the 1956 O'Brien theatrical film version. Pleasence had also appeared in the BBC television version, playing the character of Syme, which for the film was amalgamated with that of the character Parsons.\n\nLike the [[Animal Farm (1954 film)|earlier film adaption]] of ''[[Animal Farm]]'', ''1984'' was secretly funded by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Morris|first1=Nigel|title=Keeping It All in the (Nuclear) Family: Big Brother, Auntie BBC, Uncle Sam and George Orwell\u2019s Nineteen Eighty-Four|journal=Frames Cinema Journal|url=http://framescinemajournal.com/article/keeping-it-all-in-the-nuclear-family-big-brother-auntie-bbc-uncle-sam-and-george-orwells-nineteen-eighty-four/}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA voice-over narrator explains that in the mid-1950s, a [[nuclear war]] and devastation of Earth gave rise to [[Nations of Nineteen Eighty-Four|three superstates]]: Oceania, Eurasia, and East Asia. By 1984, London, with its bomb-proof ministry, is designated as the capital of Airstrip One, a province of Oceania, controlled by one all-powerful Party, embodied by the figurehead [[Big Brother (1984)|Big Brother]].\n\nIn the spring of 1984, [[Winston Smith]], a member of the elite Outer Party, encounters [[Julia (1984)|Julia]], a woman he suspects may be a member of the [[Thought Police]]. Winston returns to his apartment, where an electronic surveillance eye examines the contents of his briefcase. Smuggling a small black diary past the eye, Winston begins to write down the subversive thoughts he fears to say aloud. Winston's reverie is interrupted when Selina Parsons, a little girl who lives next door, enters his apartment to practice denouncing him as a traitor. Robert Parsons, Selina's father, invites Winston to join him at the local Chestnut Tree caf\u00e9.\n\nAt the cafe, Winston and Parsons spot Rutherford and Jones, two Outer Party traitors who have been rehabilitated by the government's Ministry of Love. Afterwards, Winston goes to a junk shop to wonder at the objects of yesteryear that are now deemed worthless. Julia enters the shop, sending Winston scurrying into the street, where he is stopped by the police and ordered to report to Administration the next morning.\n\nAt the Administration the next day, a party officer reprimands Winston for socializing with the common masses. Winston then proceeds to his job at the Records Department at the Ministry of Truth. When Winston discovers a photo that would prove Jones and Rutherford innocent, [[O'Brien (1984)|O'Connor]], Winston's superior, instructs him to destroy it.\n\nThat evening, at a political rally, Julia passes Winston a note professing her love to him. Later, they arrange to meet Sunday in a meadow outside London, far from the prying microphones and monitors of Big Brother. There, they touch each other, an act prohibited by the Anti-Sex League, and proceed to make love.\n\nTwo weeks later, Winston proposes renting a room at the junk store, one of the few places free of the omnipresent monitors. In the sanctity of their quarters, Winston confides that he believes O'Connor may be a member of the Underground.\n\nOne night, Winston finds a note written in O'Connor's handwriting that reads \"down with Big Brother.\" Convinced that O'Connor represents their only hope to break free of the tyranny of Big Brother, Julia and Winston go to his apartment and declare that they want to join the Underground. O'Connor instructs Winston to carry an empty briefcase with him at all times.\n\nA few days later, during a rally to launch Hate Week, a man switches briefcases with Winston. When Winston opens the case, he finds a copy of a treatise by the alleged leader of the Underground. Back in their secret room, Julia muses that only love can defeat Big Brother. At that moment, a telescreen hidden behind a mirror condemns Julia's sentiments, after which, the police burst in to arrest them.\n\nAt the Ministry of Love, Winston is confined in a pit-like room. Soon after, Parsons is thrown into the pit, his daughter having denounced him for muttering in his sleep \"Down with Big Brother.\" After Parsons is taken away, O'Connor enters the room and reveals himself to be a covert agent of the state. Under O'Connor's direction, Winston is subjected to a brainwashing campaign. Still resistant after a series of electroshock treatments, Winston declares that the party will never eradicate his love for Julia. Having ascertained that Winston's worst fear is being eaten alive by rats, O'Connor confines him in a room filled with the squealing rodents, after which Winston breaks down and begs them to feed Julia to the rodents instead.\n\nAfter O'Connor authorizes his release, Winston mindlessly wanders through the streets, where he spots Julia. After they confess their mutual betrayal, Big Brother broadcasts that the Eurasian army has been routed in battle and that the war will be soon over. In the final shot, the rehabilitated and brainwashed Winston and Julia then fervently join the crowd in cheering \"Long live Big Brother!\"\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Edmond O'Brien]] as [[Winston Smith]]\n* [[Michael Redgrave]] as [[O'Brien (Nineteen Eighty-Four)|General O'Connor]]\n* [[Jan Sterling]] as [[Julia (Nineteen Eighty-Four)|Julia]]\n* [[David Kossoff]] as Charrington\n* [[Mervyn Johns]] as Jones\n* [[Donald Pleasence]] as R. Parsons\n* Carol Wolveridge as Selina Parsons\n* [[Ernest Clark]] as Outer Party Announcer\n* [[Patrick Allen]] as Inner Party Official\n* [[Michael Ripper]] as Outer Party Orator\n* [[Ewen Solon]] as Outer Party Orator\n* [[Kenneth Griffith]] as Prisoner\n\n==Reception==\n''[[New York Times]]'' reviewer [[A.H. Weiler]]  called this film adaptation a stark, sober and thoughtful, if not altogether persuasive, film.\" He said the film  The \"director and the scenarists have adapted the book 'freely.' But they have retained its essential spirit and ideas in the film.\"<ref name=\"Weller\">{{cite news |last1=Weiler |first1=A. H. |title=The Screen: '1984' Opens; Adaptation of Orwell's Novel at Normandie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/10/01/archives/the-screen-1984-opens-adaptation-of-orwells-novel-at-normandie.html |accessdate=30 November 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=1 October 1956}}</ref> A ''[[The Boston Globe|Boston Globe]]'' reviewer said that \"the film had the same sense of bleak horror and black apprehension that Orwell developed when freedom was allowed to die.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39863267/screen_arrivals_pilgrim_offers_grim/|title=SCREEN ARRIVALS: Pilgrim Offers Grim '1984'|last=Adams|first=Marjorie|date=1956-07-26|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=2019-11-30|pages=19}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of films featuring surveillance]]\n*[[List of films that depict class struggle]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0048918|title=1984}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|1209731-1984|1984}}\n\n{{Nineteen Eighty-Four}}\n{{Michael Anderson}}\n<!--Split film/book article intentional - Please do not remove this comment-->\n\n[[Category:1956 films]]\n[[Category:1950s science fiction drama films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British science fiction drama films]]\n[[Category:British black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films based on Nineteen Eighty-Four]]\n[[Category:Dystopian films]]\n[[Category:Films about freedom of expression]]\n[[Category:Mass surveillance in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films set in the future]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1984]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Michael Anderson]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Malcolm Arnold]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:the work's name is \"The New York Times\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1984_(1956_film)"}
{"title_page": "1955 in literature", "text_new": "{{Year nav topic5|1955|literature|poetry}}\n\nThis article presents lists of the literary events and publications in '''1955'''.\n<!-- Redlinks will be removed. Add pages as you write them. -->\n<!-- formerly (18apr07): ''See also:'' [[1954 in literature]], [[1955|other events of 1955]], [[1956 in literature]], [[list of years in literature]].-->\n==Events==\n*[[February 8]] \u2013 [[Jin Yong]]'s first ''[[wuxia]]'' novel, ''[[The Book and the Sword]]'' (\u66f8\u528d\u6069\u4ec7\u9304), begins publication in the ''[[New Evening Post]]'' (Hong Kong), where he is an editor.\n*[[April 16]] \u2013 Sir [[Laurence Olivier]]'s film version of Shakespeare's ''[[Richard III (1955 film)|Richard III]]'' is released in U.K. cinemas.\n*[[July 10]] \u2013 [[Jorge Luis Borges]] is appointed Director of the [[National Library of the Argentine Republic]].\n*[[July 14]] \u2013 Director [[Stephen Joseph]] sets up Britain's first [[theatre in the round]] at [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire]], predecessor of the [[Stephen Joseph Theatre]].<ref>{{Cite web |first=Simon |last=Murgatroyd |title=Scarborough In The Round |url=http://www.theatre-in-the-round.co.uk/index.html |accessdate=2015-11-23}}</ref>\n*[[July 30]] \u2013 The English poet [[Philip Larkin]], having become University Librarian at the [[University of Hull]] on March 21, is inspired on a train from [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] to [[Grantham]] to write a poem, \"[[The Whitsun Weddings (poem)|The Whitsun Weddings]]\".<ref>Contrary to his later recollection of the event. {{Cite book |editor=Burnett, Archie |title=The Complete Poems of Philip Larkin |location=London |publisher=Faber |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-571-24006-7 |page=411}}</ref> His collection ''[[The Less Deceived]]'' is published in November (dated October).\n*August \u2013 The American [[speculative fiction]] author [[Charles Beaumont]]'s short story \"The Crooked Man\", depicting a homosexual society where heterosexuality is persecuted, is published in ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine after being rejected by ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''.\n*[[August 3]] \u2013 The English-language premi\u00e8re of [[Samuel Beckett]]'s play ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'', directed by [[Peter Hall (director)|Peter Hall]], opens at the [[Arts Theatre]], London.\n*[[August 27]] \u2013 The first hardback edition of ''[[Guinness World Records|The Guinness Book of Records]]'' appears in London.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Guinness Book History 1950 \u2013 Present |url=http://spyhunter007.com/spy_guinness_book_history.htm |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref>\n*September \u2013 [[Vladimir Nabokov]]'''s [[Lolita]]'' appears in Paris three years before its US publication.<ref>{{Cite book |first=Brian |last=Boyd |title=Vladimir Nabokov: The American Years |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=1991 |isbn=0-691-06797-X |page=[https://archive.org/details/vladimirnabokova00boyd/page/226 226] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/vladimirnabokova00boyd}}</ref>\n*November \u2013 [[Frank Herbert]]'s first novel ''[[The Dragon in the Sea]]'' begins as a three-part serialization, ''Under Pressure'', in the monthly ''[[Analog Science Fiction and Fact|Astounding Science-Fiction]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kirjasto.sci.fi/fherbert.htm |title=Frank (Patrick) Herbert |website=Books and Writers |first=Petri |last=Liukkonen |publisher=[[Kuusankoski]] Public Library |location=Finland |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427010107/http://www.kirjasto.sci.fi/fherbert.htm|archivedate=2014-04-27 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[November 28]] \u2013 [[Ray Lawler]]'s ''[[Summer of the Seventeenth Doll]]'' is first staged by the [[Melbourne Theatre Company|Union Theatre Repertory Company]] in [[Melbourne]] with the playwright in a lead. It is the first authentically naturalistic modern drama in the [[theatre of Australia]].<ref>{{Cite book |first=Peter |last=Fitzpatrick |title=After The Doll: Australian Drama Since 1955 |publisher=Edward Arnold Australia |location=Melbourne |year=1979 |series=Studies in Australian culture |isbn=0726720402 |page=[https://archive.org/details/afterthedollaust0000fitz/page/ vii] |url=https://archive.org/details/afterthedollaust0000fitz/page/}}</ref>\n\n''Uncertain dates''\n*[[Jean Cocteau]] is elected to the ''[[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]]'' (March 3; inducted October 20) and the ''[[The Royal Academies for Science and the Arts of Belgium|Acad\u00e9mie royale des Sciences, des Lettres et des Beaux-Arts de Belgique]]'' (January 8/October 1).\n*An article in the ''[[British Journal of Education]]'' criticises [[Enid Blyton]]'s novels as [[formula fiction|formulaic]].<ref>{{Cite book |first=Robert |last=Druce |title=This Day Our Daily Fictions: an enquiry into the multi-million bestseller status of Enid Blyton and Ian Fleming |location=Amsterdam |publisher=Rodopi |year=1992 |chapter=Chapter 4 |isbn=90-5183-401-2 |series=Costerus, n. s. vol. 84.}}</ref>\n*The Indian guru [[Mani Madhava Chakyar]] performs [[Koodiyattam]] outside a temple for the first time.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Bhargavinilayam |first=Das |title=Mani Madhaveeyam |publisher=Department of Cultural Affairs, [[Government of Kerala]] |year=1999 |isbn=81-86365-78-8}}</ref>\n\n==New books==\n===Fiction===\n[[File:Lolita 1955.JPG|thumb|1st ed.]]\n*[[Kingsley Amis]] \u2013 ''[[That Uncertain Feeling (novel)|That Uncertain Feeling]]''\n*[[Isaac Asimov]]\n**''[[The End of Eternity]]''\n**''[[The Martian Way and Other Stories]]''\n*[[Elisabeth Augustin]] \u2013 ''Labyrinth (Auswege)''\n*[[Nigel Balchin]] \u2013 ''[[The Fall of the Sparrow]]''\n*[[Antoine Blondin]] \u2013 ''[[L'Humeur vagabonde]]''\n*[[Leigh Brackett]] \u2013 ''[[The Long Tomorrow (novel)|The Long Tomorrow]]''\n*[[Ray Bradbury]] \u2013 ''[[The October Country]]''\n*[[Henry Cecil Leon|Henry Cecil]] \u2013 ''[[Brothers in Law (novel)|Brothers in Law]]''\n*[[Louis-Ferdinand C\u00e9line]] \u2013 ''[[Conversations with Professor Y]] (Entretiens avec le professeur Y)''\n*[[Agatha Christie]] \u2013 ''[[Hickory Dickory Dock (novel)|Hickory Dickory Dock]]''\n*[[Arthur C. Clarke]] \u2013 ''[[Earthlight]]''\n*[[Ivy Compton-Burnett]] \u2013 ''Mother and Son''\n*[[Thomas B. Costain]] \u2013 ''The Tontine''\n*[[Marco Denevi]] \u2013 ''Rosaura a las 10'' (Rosaura at 10 O'Clock)\n*[[Patrick Dennis]] \u2013 ''[[Auntie Mame]]''\n*[[John Dickson Carr]] \u2013 ''Captain Cut-Throat''\n*[[J. P. Donleavy]] \u2013 ''[[The Ginger Man]]''\n*[[Friedrich D\u00fcrrenmatt]] \u2013 ''[[Once a Greek]] (Grieche sucht Griechin)''\n*[[Mircea Eliade]] \u2013 ''[[The Forbidden Forest]] (Noaptea de S\u00e2nziene)''\n*[[Ian Fleming]] \u2013 ''[[Moonraker (novel)|Moonraker]]''\n*[[Andr\u00e9 Franquin]] \u2013 ''La Corne de rhinoc\u00e9ros''\n*[[Gillian Freeman]] \u2013 ''The Liberty Man''\n*[[William Gaddis]] \u2013 ''[[The Recognitions]]''\n*[[Gao Yubao]] (with Guo Yongjiang) \u2013 ''Gao Yubao''\n*[[David Garnett]] \u2013 ''[[Aspects of Love (novel)|Aspects of Love]]''\n*[[William Golding]] \u2013 ''[[The Inheritors (Golding novel)|The Inheritors]]''\n*[[Graham Greene]]\n**''[[The Quiet American]]''\n**''[[Loser Takes All]]''\n*[[Henri Ren\u00e9 Guieu]]\n**''L'Agonie du Verre''\n**''Commandos de l'Espace''\n**''Univers parall\u00e8les''\n*[[Robert A. Heinlein]] \u2013 ''[[Tunnel in the Sky]]''\n*[[Georgette Heyer]] \u2013 ''[[Bath Tangle]]''\n*[[Patricia Highsmith]] \u2013 ''[[The Talented Mr. Ripley]]''\n*[[Robert E. Howard]] and [[L. Sprague de Camp]] \u2013 ''[[Tales of Conan]]''\n*[[Aldous Huxley]] \u2013 ''[[The Genius and the Goddess]]''\n*[[Mac Hyman]] \u2013 ''[[No Time for Sergeants]]''\n*[[Roger Ikor]] \u2013 ''Les Eaux m\u00eal\u00e9es''\n*[[Dan Jacobson]] \u2013 ''The Trap''\n*[[Robin Jenkins]] \u2013 ''[[The Cone Gatherers]]''\n*[[Ruth Prawer Jhabvala]] \u2013 ''To Whom She Will''\n*[[MacKinlay Kantor]] \u2013 ''[[Andersonville (novel)|Andersonville]]''\n*[[Nikos Kazantzakis]] \u2013 ''[[The Last Temptation of Christ 